Feels like a good concept on paper, but it's been executed poorly. The towers tend to clash in appearance when put together, which comes from having 4 or 5 different races and themes on the screen at the same time. While there are certainly good looking elements there are too many bad ones to ignore. The audio is odd too. The background music is like 30 seconds long and loops throughout much of the game. I'd had enough of it by the end of the first level and then it plays for much much longer. Also the game has been even further mobilised with many more micro transactions and giving you cards with resources and abilities on them every level. Theres also the problem with the overall theme, but that's something I could look past. It doesn't make much sense for an invading army to be building towers defending a path but whatever - it doesn't affect the gameplay. While there will certainly be people who like the game, I found that having biker goblins next to joke telling demons next to medival knights next to fishmen reaaaaaaly put me off. And theres not enough towers of 1 race or theme to really keep it clean.

content: Many people leave negative reviews not knowing what they're getting themselves into. First of all, this game is HARD. You're going to have to make quick decisions. Gems are also easy to obtain (~75-150 gems per level, 999 gems for max powerup.) This is a phenomenal tower defense game for the mobile market.

In many ways, it's a proper Kingdom Rush with lovely art style and gameplay. Unfortunately, the slowly advancing greed of Ironhide is beginning to make gameplay terrible. There are purchaseable heroes, towers, and gems which often seem frustratingly necessary to win. I am also disappointed that it's becoming more of an action game than a strategic one. I'm constantly tapping to deploy units, unfreeze my towers , and I resort to using consumables more than ever. Please consider these observations.

I don't write reviews, but extremely annoyed about people claiming the game is too hard and that pay to win is the only way to complete the game.   I have completed every KR game, campaign mission, heroic and iron challenges (except for 1 in the first game) with 3 stars ratings, without letting 1 enemy slip, and the best part?? I have not spent a penny on any in-app purchases. I did not even buy the gem store items as I feel they are too OP and ruin game play exp.   Stage is too hard? Try different tower placements and combinations. Not enough towers? We now have 11 to choose from instead of 8. Heroes/Towers are behind a pay wall? ALL IAP are not required at all to complete the game. Not enough content? For the previous 3 games in the series, updates + endless mode has ALWAYS come after they release the game.  There is nothing Pay to Win in this game. NONE of the in-app purchases are required to beat the game. If you still say the game is too hard, I'm sorry but learn the game, learn the stage, learn the towers, learn the enemies, or just get good.   Ironhide Game, keep doing what you are doing. I look forward to future updates and the next KR.   FOR THE KING !!

A really beautiful and fun to play game. It's sad that it is burdened with close to $80 worth of micro-transactions. This game is not a AAA title, and should not have a price that puts it in that league. Ironhide is even scummy enough to push you into making poor purchasing decisions by having a limited time sale to unlock heroes/towers at a discount. This is an amazing series that has really been ruined by greed. You pay for the game, and then find out that if you want all of the content it's going to cost you $80. I'd refund the amount I paid to buy the game in the first place if I still could, just to send the message that these practices are not acceptable. Do yourself a favour and pass on this game. There are other good games out there that won't require you to empty your wallet just to get what you paid for. Kingdom Rush Vengeance is the equivalent of buying a Ferrari for a decent price, but when you go to drive it off the lot you find out the tires are half full, the interior has been gutted, and someone replaced the engine with one from a lawn mower. Technically it drives, but you're not getting the experience you expected.  Has frozen several times as well.

There are a lot of enhancement here compared to the previous titles. The visual aspect, the animation, the new mechanic within the tired tower defense genre, all are polished. The soundwork, well, I'm sorry to say that it's a bit disappointing, sfx is fine but the background music leaves me no impression. A couple of experimental features are here, at least I'm pleased that the team always attempt to think out of the box. The new towers system provides a fresh change, it's a bit sudden (well, I'm kinda sad, I missed the old 8 specialized towers), you guys really nailed the balance among all. What's important needs to repeat: visual great, animation polished. There Nevertheless, I share the common complaint: WHERE IS THE ENCYCLOPEDIA? Well, since Towers have their own description, you could only need to make an "enemy almanac" instead?

content: The game itself is great I just wish you could purchase the additional towers, and heroes with in game currency or something.

Despite what some other reviewers seem to imply, the game is not too difficult at all. In fact, I found it easier than other titles in the Kingdom Rush series, some of which were nearly impossible in the final levels. I've basically finished each level after the first attempt, most of them with 3 stars (I'm talking about the casual mode, of course). Also, you've got plenty of towers and 3 heroes to choose from, without having to pay for the extra heroes and towers. Of course, having to pay for extra stuff after paying for the game is controversial, but since the game can be easily completed without those extra items and there's plenty of free towers and heroes to choose from, I wouldn't complain about that. The only thing I have to complain about - something which is common to all the Kingdom Rush titles - is the fact that in order to call a new wave you have to pan to the edge of the screen, which is cumbersome and annoying (hence one star less).

content: I love every game in this series and they nailed it again. Totally worth the money. The tower designs are amazing.

The game itself is great, It's a Kingdom Rush game after all. The only Thing that has changed, that I really don't like is the new upgrade system. Most of the upgrades feel very lackluster. On top of that, you can no longer earn extra stars from Heroic and Iron Challenges (unlike in every other Kingdom Rush game). So you might wonder, why should you do those extra levels, which are more difficult? You shouldn't, because they don't give you any meaningful reward anymore, other than a few more gems, which is their premium currency. Heroic and Iron Challenges used to be something fun and challenging you could do in order to get some extra upgrades points for an early advantage. It was like doing side quests in an RPG game to get a couple extra levels before progressing through the main story. Now there is no point, unless you just want a few dozen extra gems I guess? Personally though, I choose to play without all the flashy cash-grab gem items, and just play the game normally. But to each their own, I guess?  EDIT: After playing the game for a couple hours I've encountered a number of very frustrating bugs, so I'll be changing the rating from a '3' to a '1' until they are fixed.

I am a huge fan of tower defense games and the kingdom rush series is my favorite above all! Pros: 1. Wide selection of towers! This version is different from the usual 4 types of tower. In this game, you get to choose a variety of free towers that best suit your gameplay. I like it very much! 2. Easter eggs and references! This is one cool feat in kingdom rush series. Im glad that you didnt remove this one. I find it entertaining but can you give me a clue where to find groot? :) 3. Switching sides! I like this concept. Now I get to fight for vez'nan's side! #vengeanceforthedarkking Cons: 1. No fast forward button! 2. Not too challenging! I completed the campaign maps in veteran mode in just a few tries with perfect life and without the use of special items. I find it odd. Kingdom rush is usually difficult. But I am still to try the impossible mode. I want to buy some towers and some heroes but if its this easy, then probably I dont need to anymore. 3. Short waves! I need more waves so that I can max upgrade a tower. I find it short when I get to finish a map without even trying to max upgrade a tower and see it's full potential. If you can complete a map without the need of max upgrading a tower, then what are the tower's special abilities for? 4. No elite maps! This makes me very disappointed. There are only 17 campaign maps (too short) and I was really looking forward for the elite maps but there are none. Why? All the other kingdom rush has elite maps and their level of difficulty is very different from the normal campaign maps. Maybe sooner you will include it? I dont know. Please answer this question. I want to know :) As of now, this is my rating for this game. I will update my review once new contents are added. Again, I love your game and I am glad that you released a new version of kingdom rush. Thank you and more power!

Cons: (1) Too short. I beat this game shortly after I got it, and i was only playing casually. (2) Re-skinned version of previous entries. If you played any of their other games, then you've essentially played this game. There's only minor deviations between this game and the others, and I even had someone ask if it was origins. (3) Requires additional payments to unlock other aspects. Similar to previous entries, you have to pay more to get some of the best heroes & towers. Pros: (1) Fun hidden details. Each level has hidden details you can find that reference various media from pop culture (Terminator, Lord of the Rings). (2) You're the bad guy this time. I was hoping there would be missions where you would send waves after waves towards the enemy castle, instead of just setting up towers, but no dice. I don't think the pros outweigh the cons, and hope they release new content (at no additional cost) to expand the game.

I am a fan of Ironhide Games, but this was disappointing. Great graphics and gameplay, but it's restrained by throttling, short duration, and microtransactions. When I say throttling, I mean the fact that the challenge modes no longer offer upgrade points like the previous games. Which leads into the next issue. Short duration. The game is short and this may be the reason challenge mode no longer give upgrade points. This game is so short I'd argue the price of the game is rip off. The microtransactions are becoming an issue. I don't have an issue buying heroes, but now I have to buy towers? The microtransactions could be excused if the game was longer and have the features remained, but that isn't the case. Overall, disappointing game, I don't recommend buying this game. Ironhide needs to do better.

So far I have purchased every game released from this studio. So far with this release I am quite impressed. Well sort of... The gameplay and hidden easter eggs are phenomenal. Lending more gameplay and strategic awareness. My only gripe would be the difficulty. Well additionally the number of levels released thus far. I see there may be intention to release additional levels due to the map size and areas unexplored. I started playing the game on Veteran. The challenge wasn't as high as the other kingdom rushes. So with their new impossible difficulty I expected to restart over and over again. Well to my dissapointment... I was able to achieve 3 stars on first playthrough on some of the mid levels. I still haven't completed every level on this difficultly but so far I'm not impressed. I love the game but the challenge just isn't there. I usually purchase the dlc to help with challenging levels but as of now there is no need to buy the additional towers other than for aesthetic purposes. I understand the dlc for characters since that's something they've always done. But for towers....blatantly a cash grab. You will already win over new customers with the high ratings. Don't fall into the cookie cutter nature of these studios nowadays. Stand out with content which is something you do well.

Kingdom Rush is far and away my favorite mobile gaming franchise and has been for almost a decade. I've been playing it since they released the original as a free flash game on Newgrounds in like 2010? 2011? This is the absolute gold standard for tower defense games. They've put their own flair into every single piece of art in this game and you can tell that every part of this game is crafted with love and attention to detail. The controls are tight but not unforgiving. The game is hard but not unbeatable even for the first time player. Kingdom Rush is also my 10 year old daughter's favorite mobile game for that exact same reason. I have no problem paying $4.99 for such a well polished product. I only wish the rest of the developers in the app store showed as much love for their craft as Ironhide does. Keep doing what you're doing devs, because it's absolutely marvelous.

It's ok, pace is slower and content is leaner than previous entries, and the changes made aren't really refinements or additions, just differences, and maybe not for the better. It suffers by comparison because the previous games were so amazingly well done. I think they want to evolve and not just repeat, you see that with the space game they did too. Ambitious, well crafted, but still awkward. The art is great, but somehow less engaging. The upgrade system is a step in the wrong direction. This is sort of the Diablo 3 to the Diablo 2 that was KR 1, 2, and 3. And somehow it just feels slower and not as well paced and more awkward and clumsier, and more random and less balanced. That last may be due to having fifteen different types of towers, the strategy on your end and on theirs just becomes a mess, because neither you nor they have a clear idea what you'll do with a map. Maybe the game is fresh and needs more patches to refine and that's all, but after so many stellar entries you would expect they would have that down.

A worth while sequel to the KR series. It brings in a new tower selection mechanics that I quile like. It feels better and more strategic than the previous same-til-upgrade split decision from games past. The story is fun and inventive, and as always the art direction is fantastic. However, I can't help but notice amist all the new and improved, the lack of some of the hallmarks of the series. Gone is the Dictionary/Bestiary providing information on the enemies. Also, there are no bonus levels unlocked across the map once the campaign is beaten. Once the campaign is done, that's pretty much it. Upgrade points are now static, so there really isn't an incentive to play the challenge modes on the campaign levels beyond achievement hunting. I do hope that the game is updated with more levels, but I really wish they were included on release, like all the other KR games.

I am a huge fan of the KR series. but this one was a disappointment to me. I don't like the new tower system. The old way meant you had a total of 8 different tower types to work with in each map. And that was made even better by each tower having a unique identity and use. And they all synergized well together. Winning wasn't about towers, it was about combinations of towers. In the other KR games I almost had at least one of each tower type on most of the later levels.  With this new system the tower design feels decidedly less polished, with many towers seeming redundant or outright useless. Putting half of them behind a paywall doesn't help. And only being able to have 5 limits options. I still go back and play the original three KR games regularly, despite long since maxing out all the starts on the hardest difficulties on them. This new one felt short, no side missions, I beat it in about an afternoon, and I feel no urge to go back and replay any of the levels after beating them like I did in the previous titles.   The other games have all provided me with hours of enjoyment, this one I completed more out of an obligation and will probable rarely, if ever, pick back up.

After the amazing triology of KR, this time it makes a comeback with a little plot twist. Still awesome as before in all aspect, gameplay, details, storyline, easter egg, music, you name it. To be specific with some noteworthy points,the whole tower system has been changed andI like it alot. While it limits the possibility of more complex combinations (only 5 specialization at a time instead of 8), it adds another layer of strategic planning pre-battle. The new skill system is also a nice improvement. I like the idea of having different route to choose with really make we think which set to choose situationally although it is still limited to just one node. For ppl with already veteran level skill, the impossible difficulty might also be a nice addition. Still there are some points I think could have been better. The achievement is as grinding demanded as ever, some achievements are just straight ridiculous. 30000ds from a crow tower skill with 4dps for example. There is not really any strategic value of such achievement. While I like the new idea in the boss battle alot. They are actually way too easy even at veteran (I know we have impossible level, but previous KR boss fights are always intense). For some reason, there is no encyclopedia, which is a disappointment especially for hard-core fans. Last but not least, selling heroes is ok but selling towers is abit overboard, not to mention the already existing gem system. I mean, look at the price, the game itself with all the contents cost even less than 1 paid tower, that is ridiculous. If you want to have more support, fans will for sure purchase some gems and all the extras. Heck, I am willing to pay 10-20 bucks for the game itself, it is definitely more solid and engaging than many other games. But the fact that players know the game experience will be restricted by some paid DLC is not nice. Still, it is a great game and a must have if you are into tower defense.

So I've been a huge fan of this series for years. I love Tower Defense games and Kingdom Rush does it better than most any other game out there. That said, this time I feel like they changed up the formula a bit and now have room to improve. I bought the heroes and towers as an investment in the series. Right now I dont feel it is worth $30, but the company does deserve it for how long they've worked to make the best defense games out there.

Ironhide keeps the quality up with this kingdom rush game...I personally love the fact these games aren't pushed out yearly like most franchises they actually take their time adding new elements and gimmicks with each game to make it feel different but at the same time feel familiar. Nothing but joy and fun playing this tower defense game. If the series continues, I will be the first to buy it.

Great addition to the kingdom rush series, runs super smoothly and looks gorgeous. I do dislike the fact that you have to pay for premium towers in this one, as I feel part of the novelty of this series is experimenting with all the different tower combinations (5 of which are behind a paywall in this game). I also think that the prices for these towers and heroes are a bit steep (11$ and 20$ Cad respectively for all of them). Going forward I would much rather pay more upfront for the game then have more IAP being added for future installments, as I understand that quality games do require quite a bit of time and cash to make. This is a series that I really love and wouldn't mind paying 15$ per game, so long as they remove all this gated content.

I supported kingdom rush from the very humble begining when it was on PC. I have also supported the series throughout the years. What i am dissapointed in is the fast that the game has become a cash grab. The core attraction of the game are its towers yet the developers feel they have to lock the best towers behind a pay wall. Previously having to buy heroes are bad enough but now we have entered the zone of pay to win. I did infact purchase both the hero and tower bundles of the game but i feel extremely cheated on. The devs have the decency to charge such a high price for the game and make their customers purchase even more to enjoy the full game. Upon purchasing these packs the game felt extremely easy and therefore it was clearly pay to win. I feel cheated on and sadly i will never be able to get a refund for those packs. Greed has unfortunately ruined what was once a great game series.

The game is fantastic overall. I've been a fan for many years of the series and this version is exciting and refreshing; I'm grateful for the new installment. Being the villains is truly fun, the heroes have a nice selection (Asra is my favourite character of all the games), the towers are cool (shadow archers 😍), and the new system is interesting. I wish the game was longer and you had more to do. There wasn't any levels where you could use guest heroes. There was an opportunity to use even more notable old heroes as enemies. I don't mind the purchases but hopefully new side quests/maps are added on. And in the next installment I would really love to have the chance to use multiple heroes on one map.

This is a kingdom rush game. If you liked the previous ones then you will like this one. The problems with it lie in signifigant content is gated even though you payed for it. Like the previous games, there is paid heroes. This was never the high point of the series as it limits the gameplay oppurtunities for most people that don't pay dozens of dollars extra. There are now also payed towers as well. This is even worse signifigant gamplay elements are now blocked out. They could have fixed this issue by having them be bought for signifigant portions of in game currency. As an example, every dollar could be translated into 1000 gems. In this case all of the purchases would be able to be bought for 3000-7000 gems. This is significant amount but can be accessed through enough gameplay. Unfortunately, in order to have access to the rest of the content, one needs to pay 52 dollars to buy all of the heroes and towers on release. None of these can be unlocked through gameplay. There are good things about the game though. The tower system that they implemented is really interesting and something I almost want to call good, if you could access all of them without having to pay additional money. The free heroes are not that bad, especially Asra. She is probably one of the best assassin type hero in all of kingdom rush. Oloth gives good magic damage and is a decent alternative. The game also is also visually really good as it runs really smoothly with what seems like better animations. The game is also harder, which is good for veteran players of the previous games. However, I cannot help but feel that this is meant to be exploitative towards newer players. If they are having trouble on recruit difficulty, the first thing they see is an add for a bundle which is always displayed on the map screen. Overall, I can't recommend buying it in its current state as too much is within a paywall from the start. I understand that ironhide needs to make money but they are heavily limiting gameplay oppurtunities and variety for additional revenue. Personally, I don't enjoy the direction these games are going and hope that they change their mind. Luckily the problems can be fixed relatively easy. The developer could add a way to get heroes and towers eventually through in game play, as mentioned earlier. Another good way would be a premium pass of sorts that automatically gets you all of the heroes and towers while removing the bundle advertisements. Ideally, this would also get you future heroes and towers. If something along these lines get implemented I will change the review to 5 stars.

It feels so good to be playing a new Kingdom Rush!!! It's better than ever and seems so far to be the most polished installment in the series so far. My only gripe is that it's also the most monetized. The $5 price for the game is more than fair, but I was not thrilled to see gated content -including premium towers, a series first. It would be less bothersome if the game didn't also reduce upgrade options for towers. Unlike prior games, this time towers do not have upgrade "trees" that allow different level 4 options. Instead you get a 5th tower slot and can swap out towers between maps. It's an interesting system that presents some new possibilities, but the reduction in the options for each individual tower seems less like a design decision and more like an arbitrary way to push premium towers sales. There are no ads, though, and there is no strategic need for the premium towers, so it's hard to give the devs too much grief for this. They do deserve to be compensated for their good work. I'm giving it 5 out 5- Kingdom Rush has long been one of the absolute best mobile game series and Vengeance continues that legacy of greatness.

My Lord Vez'nan commands me to inform you that his armies are unstoppable. Join us and take command of orc warriors, demonic mages and more. Eleven towers will be unlocked throughout the campaign, with five more requiring extra funds to purchase. Mighty heroes will fight for darkness by your side, though only three are available; the others require further donations. Vez'nan's powers are at their height! The graphics are clear and bright, animations crisp, and the controls are impeccable. Some may be dismayed by the added cost of premium towers and heroes. But this is war, and sacrifices are required. Now is your chance to support the legions of Ironhide. Vez'nan will look kindly on you if you do. Join him, and evil shall rule the lands once more!

Ironhide are back with yet another amazing game. Kingdom Rush Vengeance is a fresh addition to what I believe is the finest tower defense series on mobile. Die hard fans of the series will enjoy the overhauled upgrade and tower systems but certainly won't miss how it has been done in previous installments. However, new players choosing Vengeance as their first Kingdom Rush experience will see the series at its finest. Your motives are clear which drives the story through the largest map in the series, featuring more levels than ever before. However, the ability to purchase powerful towers creates a pay to win atmosphere and is certainly not a welcome cash grab.

This is hands down the best tower defense game series on the mobile platform, and in my opinion, this iteration is the best of the series. I purchased Vengeance on the day it was released, and promptly completed the campaign within the day. Not to say that it isn't challenging or that it doesn't have much content, I just enjoyed it so much that's all I did the entire day. The different tower loadout system is extremely clever and I personally think it's one of the best things about this game, and, as one of the first (or possibly THE first) people to complete the campaign, it was very well done as well. The bosses are great, and the comic cuts are terrific. All in all, great game, and I totally recommend it to anyone, ever, regardless of what style of gamer you are. Thanks for the great game guys!

Ironhide have done it again with another amazing entry to the series. Its just as charmful and humorous as the the previous 3 Kingsom Rush games, which new and old players will love. However the fact that this is the most expensive Kingdom Rush to date, coupled with the fact that FIVE towers are locked behind a paywall is ridiculous in a tower defence game. Where the core of the game is coming up with different strategies using different towers. Having heros locked behind paywalls was fine in the past and still is, as the free ones are more than capable of beating everything in the game. Purchasing these heros was a nice way of supporting the developers more whilst not effecting gameplay in a huge way. To purchase all towers and heros along with the base game will cost $30, which will never be worth it for a mobile game. Ironhide have fallen into the microtransaction trap, along with many other once great developers, now turned greedy. Disappointed. A simple solution would be to change the "premium towers" to cost a large amount of in game currency. This gives the player the choice to grind for them or to pay for them. Having them completely locked from the game unless you spend extra is the problem here.
replyContent:
Hi Mason, in KRV you have more towers than in the previous KR. Now you unlock them by playing and this time you are able to make all the combinations you want. The premium ones are just extras if you want to experiment more. 
However, if you aren't enjoying the game you can get a refund here: https://www.ironhidegames.com/Support
